But I will also confess that I'm not as nervous as I should be because I'm pretty sure I'm right about this on that, This, in fact, will be the way that we treat cancer in the future. In order to talk about cancer, I'm going to actually have to me get the big slide here. First, I'm gonna try to give you a different perspective of genomics. They want to put in perspective of some of the bigger picture of all the other things they're going on and then talk about something you haven't heard so much about which is proteomics. Having explained those that will set up for what I think will be a different idea about how to go about treating cancer. So let me start with genomics. It is the hot topic. It is the place where we're learning the most. It's the great frontier, but it has its limitations and in particular, you've probably all heard the analogy that the genome is like the blueprint of your body, and if that were only true, it would be great. But it's not. It's like the parts list of your body. It doesn't say how things were connected, what causes what and so on. So if I could make an analogy, let's say that you were trying to tell the difference between a good restaurant, a healthy restaurant and a sick restaurant, and all you had was the list of ingredients that they had in their larder. So it might be that if you went to a French restaurant and you look through a new family only had margin and they didn't have butter. You could say, I see what's wrong with them. I could make them healthy. And there probably are special cases that you could certainly tell the difference between a Chinese restaurant in a French restaurant by what they had a lawyer. So the list of ingredients does tell you something, and sometimes it tells you something that's wrong. If they have tons of salt, you might guess they're using to my salt or something like that. But it's limited because really to know if it's a healthy restaurant. If you need to taste the food, you need to know what what goes on the kitchen. You need the product of all of those ingredients. So if I if I look at a person and I look at a person's genome, it's the same thing. The genome, really the part of the genome that we can read is the list of ingredients. And so indeed, there are times when we confined in ingredients that this bad cystic fibrosis is an example of a disease where, you know you just have a bad ingredient and you have a disease, and we can actually make it direct correspondence between the ingredient in the disease. But most things you really have to know what's going on in the kitchen. Because mostly sick people used to be healthy people. They had the same genome, so the genome really tells you much more about predisposition. So what you can tell is you can tell the difference between an Asian person and a European person by looking in the ingredients list.
